s. The authors show that the top entrepreneurs in the family, the direct descendants of its founder, remain the acknowledged leaders of the kin, each one ruling his business as a patron-owner through a network of clienty2Drelatives. Other family members, though belonging to the middle class, identify ideologically with the family leadership and the bourgeoisie, and family values tend to overrule considerations of strictly business interest even among entrepreneurs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aElite (Social sciences)zMexico. 0aFamilieszMexico. 0aFamily corporationszMexico. 0aKinshipzMexico. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  aAction group.  aAffinal relations.  aAgriculture.  aAmbilocality.  aAnticlericalism.  aBoard meetings.  aBridal showers.  aBusiness luncheons.  aCapital accumulation.  aCatechization.  aCaudillos.  aChaperoning.  aChildbirth.  aCristero Rebellion.  aDirect descent.  aDíaz Ordaz, Gustavo.  aElites in Latin America.  aEngagement.  aExchange relationships.  aExport market.  aFeatherbedding.  aForeigners as elite.  aFunerals.  aGeneration gaps.  aGodparents.  aGrand tours as status symbol.  aGómez Benítez grandfamily.  aHorseback promenade.  aHueyapan.  aIllegitimate children.  aInvestment, Gómez attitude.  aJalisco.  aJuárez, Benito.  aKindred.  aKorean War.  aLinear relations.  aMale ideal.  aMating norms.  aMayorazgo.  aMexican nationalism.  aNational Association of Bankers.  aNeolocality.  aOil boom.  aPatrifocality of Gómez.  aPorfirio Díaz (General).  aRacial attitudes.  aRecession of 1926.  aRevolutionary leaders.  aSilver mining.  aTepoztlan.  aTextile industry.  aTzoltzil.  aUtilitarianism.  aValue system.1 aPérez-Lizaur, Marisol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.lo